comment:
So, here's how it's used:

Let's say we need to create a volume.

We know the CloudStack account the volume is associated with. We use this info when calling SolidFireUtil.getSolidFireAccountName to find the name of the SolidFire account that should support this CloudStack account (such a SolidFire account may not exist at this point).

We then use the String that comes back from SolidFireUtil.getSolidFireAccountName and look up the SolidFire account (making an API call to the SolidFire SAN).

If it returns a SolidFire account, we use it. Otherwise, we create a SolidFire account with that name and use it.

The method in question (`getSolidFireAccountName`) does not create anything, right? At least I could not see anything there. It basically defines/generates a name that you then use do to some processing (I believe the processing you just described).

Correct, it just gives you the name of the SolidFire account that corresponds to the applicable CloudStack account. Maybe a better name is getCorrespondingSolidFireAccountName? I could change the implementation to accept an Account and then just pull out of the Account object what I need (UUID and ID) to create the name of the SolidFire account.

That sounds a bit better.

However, if `get` is being used as a synonym for `retrieve` that should also work, which seems to be this case. English is my second language so, I might be (probably am) mistaken.

@mike-tutkowski @rafaelweingartner looking at the method it does not seem to be getting or retrieving anything, just processing the parameters to produce a valid name, hence my format-prefix sugestion.
Thinking about the `String.format` method, where you send the "pattern" and then the parameters to create a new String. I do believe that the `format` as a prefix looks good.

It's not necessary (redundant) to log console errors at these component layers.

comment:
@tomball - We have two types of processors here:
1) ServiceLoader processors (captured by serviceIterator.hasNext())
2) -processor processors

If we don't check for options.getProcessors() here and there are no service processors present, we'd never run the preprocessing step, even if we specify the -processor flag. This is why I'm currently checking both here and running pre-processing if either is present (which tests corroborate).

There is a slight change to the way j2objc currently operate, as the -processor flag is currently ignored and will now override any ServiceLoader processor, due to the interface defined by javac (and also documented in the j2objc -help documentation of the -processor flag)

comment: What does this `validate` method does?
`validate(timeout)` waits till the testClient collects and validates the messages from the server asynchronously.
Does it block for 10s, or will it finish before if the message has been received in, say, 1s?
I just finished the review, and I still don't quite understand the validate... Can't you use a `CountDownLatch` here?

> Does it block for 10s, or will it finish before if the message has been received in, say, 1s?
 
 10s is just the timeout for the collecting of conversation reports. If the reports are available earlier, then they are validated immediately.

> I still don't quite understand the validate... Can't you use a CountDownLatch here?
 
 `TestWebSocketClient` uses `BlockingQueue` internally. Perhaps it could be replaced with `CountDownLatch` or some other sync. mech, but I do not see much profit there.
OK, the idea would be to have the test to be explicit about what is going on. But this is a matter of taste, I suppose :)
Why the `//` at the end of the line ?
So that Eclipse's `CTRL+F` (Format) does not join the lines.
